                <fr:anchor>8619</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">//forester/jms-00RJ</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>foreign-forester-jms-00RJ.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Emitting XML and resolving namespaces">Emitting XML and resolving namespaces</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Since <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00CW.xml" title="Forester 3.0" addr="//forester/jms-00CW" type="local">version 3.0</fr:link>, <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00CZ.xml" title="Forester 3.0 › breaking changes › fall-through of undefined identifiers" addr="//forester/jms-00CZ" type="local">Forester’s source language has supported</fr:link> a limited form of custom XML output by means of the <fr:code><![CDATA[\xml]]></fr:code> command. This support was, however, somewhat unwieldy: no built-in accounting for XML namespaces was included, so correct  usage of <fr:code><![CDATA[\xml]]></fr:code> was prohibitively difficult because of the need for <fr:code>xmlns</fr:code> attributes on essentially every node.</fr:p>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="//forester/jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:anchor>8616</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="user">//forester/jms-00RK</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>foreign-forester-jms-00RK.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:title text="XML namespace declaration">XML namespace declaration</fr:title>
                    <fr:taxon>Feature</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <fr:p>Forester treats XML namespace prefixes in a way that respects <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex>-equivalence: in other words, any prefix mentioned must be <fr:em>bound</fr:em>, and it is possible for two different textually identical namespace prefixes to denote different namespaces depending on their scope. This makes it possible to compose code that emits XML without coordinating namespace prefixes, which I have found to be a major impediment to the correct use of XML for non-trivial work.</fr:p>
                    <fr:p>An XML namespace prefix is bound by a declaration like the following:</fr:p>
                    <fr:pre><![CDATA[\xmlns:html{http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml}]]></fr:pre>
                    <fr:p>This declaration has the same scoping rules as <fr:code><![CDATA[\def]]></fr:code>.</fr:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="//forester/jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:anchor>8617</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="user">//forester/jms-00RM</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>foreign-forester-jms-00RM.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:title text="XML literals">XML literals</fr:title>
                    <fr:taxon>Feature</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <fr:p>The old <fr:code><![CDATA[\xml]]></fr:code> syntax has been replaced with a new convenient notation for XML literals that supports <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00RK.xml" title="Forester 4.0 › enhanced XML support › emitting XML and resolving namespaces › XML namespace declaration" addr="//forester/jms-00RK" type="local">declared XML namespace prefixes</fr:link>. The grammar of XML literals is summarised below:</fr:p>
                    <fr:pre><![CDATA[qname ::= prefix:name | name
expr ::= ... | \<qname>[qname]{expr}...{expr}]]></fr:pre>
                    <fr:p>For example, if the prefix <fr:code>html:</fr:code> is bound to <fr:link href="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" type="external">http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml</fr:link> as in <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00RK.xml" title="Forester 4.0 › enhanced XML support › emitting XML and resolving namespaces › XML namespace declaration" addr="//forester/jms-00RK" type="local">Feature <fr:contextual-number addr="//forester/jms-00RK" /></fr:link>, the expression <fr:code><![CDATA[\<html:mark>[class]{highlight}{some highlighted text}]]></fr:code> will emit the following XML:</fr:p>
                    <fr:pre><![CDATA[<html:mark
  xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
  class="highlight">
 some highlighted text
</html:mark>]]></fr:pre>
                    <fr:p>In reality, the appropriate <fr:code>@xmlns:html</fr:code> attribute will be attached only where it is needed in keeping with the hierarchical structure of the XML tree. Note that when the same textual prefix is bound to two different namespaces, one of them will be automatically <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex>-renamed so as to result in correct XML with the intended semantics.</fr:p>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
                <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:authors>
                      <fr:author>
                        <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="//forester/jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                      </fr:author>
                    </fr:authors>
                    <fr:date>
                      <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                      <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                      <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                    </fr:date>
                    <fr:anchor>8618</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="user">//forester/jms-00RL</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>foreign-forester-jms-00RL.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:title text="A worked example">A worked example</fr:title>
                    <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter>
                    <fr:p>The following code causes MathML to be emitted (in the correct namespace), combining <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00RK.xml" title="Forester 4.0 › enhanced XML support › emitting XML and resolving namespaces › XML namespace declaration" addr="//forester/jms-00RK" type="local">Feature <fr:contextual-number addr="//forester/jms-00RK" /></fr:link> and <fr:link href="foreign-forester-jms-00RM.xml" title="Forester 4.0 › enhanced XML support › emitting XML and resolving namespaces › XML literals" addr="//forester/jms-00RM" type="local">Feature <fr:contextual-number addr="//forester/jms-00RM" /></fr:link>:</fr:p>
                    <fr:pre><![CDATA[\xmlns:mml{http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML}
\<mml:math>[display]{block}{
 \<mml:mrow>{
  \<mml:msup>{
   \<mml:mi>{x}
   \<mml:mn>{2}
  }
  \<mml:mo>{+}
  \<mml:mi>{x}
 }
}]]></fr:pre>
                    <fr:p>The above displays as follows:</fr:p>
                    <mml:math display="block" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
    <mml:mrow xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
     <mml:msup xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
      <mml:mi xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">x</mml:mi>
      <mml:mn xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">2</mml:mn>
     </mml:msup>
     <mml:mo xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">+</mml:mo>
     <mml:mi xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">x</mml:mi>
    </mml:mrow>
   </mml:math>
                  </fr:mainmatter>
                </fr:tree>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
